# basic-delivery example — operator-editable configuration (NO SECRETS).
#
# This file is sourced by run.sh. It carries only the knobs an operator may
# change; the launch script translates these into the production
# temper-worker / temper-provision-forgejo CLI flags. CLI overrides always win
# over what is set here, which in turn overrides the binaries' own defaults.
#
# Secrets (per-role tokens/passwords, any API key) never live here — see
# ../secrets/ and ../secrets/.env.example.
#
# This is the "happy path, nothing fancy" counterpart to reference-delivery:
# ONE repo, THREE roles (architect, engineer, mechanical-as-bot) + CI, webhooks
# on, and landing gated on CI alone — no reviewer, owner, or human in the loop.

# --- Repository ---------------------------------------------------------------
# The example is deliberately single-repo. OWNER/NAME identify the one org+repo
# run.sh provisions, seeds, and scans. There is no REPOS set, no cross-repo
# fan-out, and no validators — keep it to one converging happy path.
OWNER=acme
NAME=service

# Default branch the repo is initialized with (the implementation PR targets it).
DEFAULT_BRANCH=main

# --- Workflow spec ------------------------------------------------------------
# The 3-role basic-delivery spec. run.sh passes this file to BOTH the provision
# and the worker invocations via Temper's --workflow flag (W1). It tracks the
# canonical Temper fixture crates/temper-workflow/fixtures/basic-delivery.json —
# keep the two in sync; do not fork its semantics here.
#
# Path is resolved relative to this example's config/ directory by run.sh.
WORKFLOW_FILE=workflow.json

# --- Seeded intake issue ------------------------------------------------------
# The single intake issue the site admin (external filer) files. It is
# DELIBERATELY THIN: it declares only the overall intent, with no acceptance
# criteria, no setting name, and no implementation detail. That is the point of
# this example — the architect must rewrite this stub into a complete,
# implementable code spec during triage (the triage_intake_to_code set_body
# effect), proving it does real design/planning work rather than just relabeling.
# Do NOT pre-bake the design here; keep the body intent-only.
#
# INTAKE_BODY_FILE is resolved relative to this config/ directory by run.sh.
INTAKE_TITLE='Service banner should identify the environment'
INTAKE_BODY_FILE=intake-issue.md

# --- Forgejo endpoint ---------------------------------------------------------
# Where the bundled throwaway Forgejo server listens. The example boots its OWN
# server on the loopback interface; a known local port is a sane default. To
# target a real Forgejo, point BASE_URL at it and drop the bundled-server/
# provisioning steps (see the README "Point it at your own Forgejo").
BASE_URL=http://127.0.0.1:4100

# --- Worker cadence / lifetime ------------------------------------------------
# Poll interval for each worker's level-triggered loop (--poll-ms), in
# milliseconds. Keep this long to prove webhooks are the latency accelerator;
# polling remains the liveness backstop if a webhook is lost.
POLL_MS=120000

# The mechanical landing worker reads CI status on this short poll because
# Forgejo 7.0.x does not send webhooks when Actions jobs complete. Leave blank to
# reuse POLL_MS. After repeated idle mechanical ticks the cadence backs off to
# IDLE_POLL_MAX_MS; wakes still interrupt immediately, and active ticks reset it.
CI_STATUS_POLL_MS=1000
IDLE_POLL_MAX_MS=8000

# Enable the local webhook accelerator from the start. The trigger broadcasts
# each accepted webhook to EVERY worker wake socket (no role routing), so the
# 3-worker pool wakes correctly. Polling remains mandatory; with WEBHOOKS=0 the
# workers run polling-only.
WEBHOOKS=1
TRIGGER_BIND=127.0.0.1:38100
WEBHOOK_URL=http://127.0.0.1:38100/forgejo/webhook

# Hard backstop on how long each worker process runs before exiting on its own
# (--run-secs). The launch script also stops workers via a stop-file sentinel;
# this is the belt-and-braces deadline. Budget several minutes for a full run.
RUN_SECS=600

# --- CPU cap (lesson 0009) ----------------------------------------------------
# The bundled Forgejo server (a Go program) can drive the host to several cores
# of sustained CPU under this multi-process workload. Cap GOMAXPROCS so the Go
# runtime cannot exceed this many cores. Set empty to opt out. Default 2.
TEMPER_FORGEJO_GOMAXPROCS=2

# --- Cached pinned binaries ---------------------------------------------------
# Absolute paths to the pinned Forgejo (7.0.12) and forgejo-runner (3.5.1)
# binaries. Leave empty to let the first run download + checksum them into
# .cache/forgejo/ (needs network to Codeberg / code.forgejo.org). On an
# offline/sandboxed host, pre-stage the binaries and point these at them.
TEMPER_FORGEJO_BINARY=
TEMPER_FORGEJO_RUNNER_BINARY=

# --- Temper entry-point binaries ----------------------------------------------
# The example targets Temper's operator-facing root-package entry points. Leave
# empty for the workspace target/debug defaults. TEMPER_BUILD_PACKAGE is the
# package run.sh builds in the development profile unless TEMPER_SKIP_BUILD=1.
TEMPER_WORKER_BIN=
TEMPER_PROVISION_BIN=
TEMPER_TRIGGER_BIN=
TEMPER_BUILD_PACKAGE=temper

# --- Smith workflow-role decision process -------------------------------------
# Temper does not ship in-process provider SDK agents. The launcher builds
# Smith's workflow-role decision responder and passes it through temper-worker's
# --role-decision-* process adapter flags. Provider/auth options are Smith-owned;
# the JSON below is copied verbatim to TEMPER_WORKER_ROLE_DECISION_ARGS_JSON.
BASIC_DELIVERY_ROLE_DECISION=smith
SMITH_WORKSPACE_ROOT=
SMITH_BUILD_PACKAGE=smith-temper-agent-cli
SMITH_WORKFLOW_ROLE_DECISION_BIN=
SMITH_WORKFLOW_ROLE_DECISION_ARGS_JSON='["--auth","chatgpt-oauth"]'
SMITH_WORKFLOW_ROLE_DECISION_ENV_ALLOWLIST=
SMITH_WORKFLOW_ROLE_DECISION_CWD=
SMITH_WORKFLOW_ROLE_DECISION_TIMEOUT_SECS=

# --- Coding workspace binding -------------------------------------------------
# The basic-delivery workflow declares two workspace external tools: the
# architect's `triage_workspace` and the engineer's `coding_workspace` (there is
# NO review_workspace — no reviewer role). One bound command backs both: temper
# invokes it per role with the right checkout capability (read-only for the
# architect, writable for the engineer) and the work-item context.
#
# BASIC_DELIVERY_CODER selects which command run.sh auto-binds when BOTH ROOT and
# COMMAND below are empty:
#   smith    (default) the real pi-SDK workspace agent (smith-coding-agent),
#            built from this Smith checkout. The engineer leaves a real product
#            diff; the architect returns the single `ready_code` verdict that
#            routes the triage. Provider/auth come from SMITH_CODING_AGENT_ARGS
#            (default `--auth chatgpt-oauth`, mirroring the role-decision
#            responder).
#   greeting the deterministic stand-in (tools/greeting-coder.sh): a fixed
#            src/banner.sh diff, no LLM, no verdicts — for an offline/CI smoke
#            run of the engineer head path.
# Set ROOT + COMMAND to your own checkout root + provider command to validate a
# different implementation path; run.sh then respects your binding verbatim.
BASIC_DELIVERY_CODER=smith
# Override the auto-built agent binary / its CLI args (provider + auth) when
# BASIC_DELIVERY_CODER=smith. Empty uses the built debug binary and
# `--auth chatgpt-oauth`.
SMITH_CODING_AGENT_BIN=
SMITH_CODING_AGENT_ARGS=
TEMPER_CODING_WORKSPACE_ROOT=
TEMPER_CODING_WORKSPACE_COMMAND=
TEMPER_CODING_WORKSPACE_REMOTE=origin
TEMPER_CODING_WORKSPACE_PUSH=1
# PR-head labels the coding workspace applies on PR creation. `implementation`
# both identifies the PR and is the `landing` queue key: with no reviewer to add
# a `landing` label, the PR enters the landing queue directly and the bot lands
# it once CI is green. (No `needs-reviewer` — there is no reviewer.)
TEMPER_CODING_WORKSPACE_PR_LABELS=implementation

# For Smith provider/auth setup, run Smith's documented preflight commands from
# the Smith checkout and edit SMITH_WORKFLOW_ROLE_DECISION_ARGS_JSON /
# allow-list above. Temper does not read provider auth files or secrets.
